<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-528-394  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 528 394.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Byte  June 1990 v15 n6 p233(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Need more fiber? It can transmit more data than copper, and it'smore secure. (fiber-optic networks)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Fisher, Sharon.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Fiber-optic network technology offers several advantages overalternative cabling technologies, including data transfer rates to100M-bits/sec (Fiber Distributed Data Interface, FDDI), superiorsecurity, no electro-magnetic radiation and optical cables betweenbuildings do not attract lightning.andP;  FDDI is the leading opticalnetwork implementation, but its $6,000 to $10,000 per node costreflects the high demurrage of current fiber optic technology.andO;The advantages of optical fiber networks are prompting firms toinstall the expensive cabling, often taking advantage of timeswhen other cabling is being installed.andP;  The trend in opticalcommunications standards is to broadband optical networktechnology, exemplified by the development of the SynchronousOptical Network interface standard and switched multimegabit dataservice on broadband optical Integrated Services Digital Network.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     TechnologyBroadbandFiber Distributed Data Interface StandardISDNOptical communicationsFiber optics.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>